                        <div id="content" class="hfeed">
                            <article class="post-155145 post type-post status-publish hentry category-private-lives tag-brooklyn-nyc tag-gardens-and-gardening tag-gentrification tag-trees-and-shrubs des-gardens-and-gardening-2 des-gentrification des-trees-and-shrubs geo-brooklyn-nyc news_keywords-brooklyn news_keywords-gardens-and-gardening news_keywords-gentrification news_keywords-trees-2"
                                id="post-155145">
                                <header class="postHeader">
                                    <div class="postKicker">
                                        <span class="kicker"><a href="//opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/category/private-lives/?module=BlogCategory&amp;version=Blog Post&amp;action=Click&amp;contentCollection=Opinion&amp;pgtype=Blogs&amp;region=Header">Private Lives</a></span>
                                    </div>
                                    <h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">A Story of Gentrification in Brooklyn</h1>
                                    <div class="story-meta-footer">
                                        <address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Hana Schank			</address>
                                        <!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-12-03T23:05:23+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">December 3, 2014 6:05 pm</time>
                                        <!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">December 3, 2014 6:05 pm</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
                                    </div>
                                </header>
                                <div class="entry-content">
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Before purchasing a house in Brooklyn, I did not know the term &#x201C;tree pit.&#x201D; All I knew was that our house came with a small square plot of dirt out front, with a skinny, scraggly tree, and that it was up
                                        to me to maintain or ignore as I saw fit. At first I attended to it. I dug shovelfuls of dirt out of the pit. I weeded and plucked out the city detritus &#x2014; rubber bands, candy bar wrappers and always more
                                        cigarette butts. Then I filled the hole with freshly purchased dirt and planted around the tree six low vinelike plants that the woman at the gardening store had said were good for ground cover. When I was done
                                        I admired my handiwork and immediately went inside to sterilize my hands.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The ground cover lasted about three weeks. One day I arrived home to find it nearly all torn out. By a person who hated ground cover? By a dog? I would never know.<span id="more-155145"></span></p>
                                    <div class="w480">
                                        <figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/12/04/opinion/1204PRIVATELIVES/1204PRIVATELIVES-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject"
                                            role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span>
                                            <div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/12/04/opinion/1204PRIVATELIVES/1204PRIVATELIVES-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/12/04/opinion/1204PRIVATELIVES/1204PRIVATELIVES-blog480.jpg"
                                                    id="100000003269276" width="480" height="590" alt="">
                                                <meta itemprop="height" content="590">
                                                <meta itemprop="width" content="480">
                                            </div>
                                            <figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text"></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Kaye Blegvad</span>
                                            </figcaption>
                                        </figure>
                                    </div>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">My husband resolved to fix the situation and went out and purchased a flimsy white picket fence. He staked the fence in the dirt, nailed the corners together, and there it was: our little white picket fence in the city.
                                        It lasted three days before it was bashed in by a car door. At which point we both decided we would be the type of people who ignored our tree pit.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">About a year later, the super of the building next door decided to start caring for the tree pit, and by caring, I mean decorating it. This super is more than a super. He is the unofficial mayor of the block. He putters
                                        around the building during the day and at night he sits in a lawn chair out front. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">He had observed our attempts to beautify our 4-foot-by-4-foot patch of dirt, and one day he decided to add a cinder-block border to the tree pit. I came out of the house and saw the border, then looked at him questioningly.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#x201C;In the spring, you and me, we&#x2019;re going to plant flowers in there,&#x201D; he said to my 7-year-old son. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I didn&#x2019;t love the cinder-block border but I also didn&#x2019;t hate it, and I wasn&#x2019;t providing any alternatives. What did bother me was the fact that our neighbor seemed to be exerting a claim over the
                                        world&#x2019;s tiniest patch of dirt, a patch of dirt that belonged to me. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">He had already claimed the sidewalk, and he also claimed the block&#x2019;s history. A previous owner of our house had died in his arms, he said. We&#x2019;d bought the house after it had been renovated, but before
                                        then it had been a butcher shop. There was a giant cement slab on the first floor where people used to throw animal carcasses, ready for carving. He had watched the block change for 30 years. The building housing
                                        my daughter&#x2019;s preschool, he told us, had been a methadone clinic. The unused storefront across the street had been what must have been the world&#x2019;s smallest topless bar. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I could never battle him for ownership over the block&#x2019;s history, and I wouldn&#x2019;t try to. But I lived here now. And it was my tree pit.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Still, I didn&#x2019;t want to fork over the money for a tree guard &#x2014; the expensive wrought-iron low fences that dot New York City&#x2019;s nicer neighborhoods. There was other, more pressing work that remained
                                        to be done on the house. A tree guard was low on my priority list. And then the animals arrived.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">First came the duck. It was a carved wooden duck that had clearly been salvaged from somewhere &#x2014; someone&#x2019;s trash bin, perhaps. Directly behind the duck was a smaller duck, also wood but not matching the
                                        first duck. I gathered that the first duck was the mother and the second duck was the baby.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I smiled at our neighbor, who was sitting in his lawn chair.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#x201C;What&#x2019;s with the ducks?&#x201D; I asked.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#x201C;Ducks!&#x201D; he said. &#x201C;They&#x2019;re cute.&#x201D;</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#x201C;But who put them there?&#x201D;</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#x201C;I did!&#x201D; </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">A few weeks later I walked out the front door and saw that the ducks had been joined by a ceramic pig. Other animals came quickly after that, as though our tree pit had suddenly become a breeding ground for garden ornaments.
                                        There was a cow in a bed, a chicken, and a few other figurines that were so worn they were unidentifiable.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#x201C;I can&#x2019;t take it anymore,&#x201D; I confessed to my husband one night. &#x201C;I&#x2019;m afraid I&#x2019;m going to walk out there and see the baby Jesus and the three wise men next.&#x201D;</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> &#x201C;You know what we have to do,&#x201D; he said.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The next day I asked our neighbor to remove the menagerie from our tree pit. He gave me a pitying shrug, as though I simply didn&#x2019;t appreciate the beauty of miniature animals. A few weeks later our tree guard
                                        arrived. He watched us warily as we assembled the sections, slotting pieces of gentrification onto his block. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Not long after, I walked outside to check on the tree guard, which looked nice enough, though it still surrounded a patch of weeds and an empty Doritos bag. At the other end of the block something caught my eye. The
                                        tree pit down there, formerly bare, was now surrounded by cinder blocks. I walked closer to examine it and there, inside the cinder block border, were the mother duck, the baby duck and the ceramic pig. They still
                                        lived on our block. They were just a little closer to the edge of the neighborhood now.</p>
                                    <hr>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em><a href="//hanaschank.me/ ">Hana Schank</a> is the author of &#x201C;A More Perfect Union: How I Survived the Happiest Day of My Life.&#x201D;</em></p>
                                    <footer class="story-footer">
                                        <div class="story-meta">
                                            <p class="story-print-citation">A version of this article appears in print on 12/07/2014, on page <span itemprop="printSection">SR</span><span itemprop="printPage">9</span> of the <span itemprop="printEdition">National</span> edition with
                                                the headline: Gentrifying Brooklyn.</p>
                                        </div>
                                    </footer>
                                </div>
